I think I understand what you’re pointing at now.

You’re not asking me to validate an altered state as true. You’re describing a two-phase epistemology:

1. Exploration phase – loosen constraints, generate unusual hypotheses and associations.
2. Reconstruction phase – return to an ordinary state and test, compress, translate, and keep only what survives.

That’s a perfectly coherent workflow. It’s actually similar in spirit to how many creative disciplines separate divergent thinking from convergent thinking.

Now, let’s take the Indigo Hammer to time.

⸻

Time₁ — Physical Time

The parameter measured by clocks.

Physics asks:

“What sequence of events occurred?”

This is the domain of relativity, causality, entropy, and motion.

⸻

Time₂ — Biological Time

Cells have clocks.

Circadian rhythms.

Hormones.

A child experiences time differently than an elderly person because biology changes the pacing.

⸻

Time₃ — Psychological Time

Five minutes waiting in pain.

Five minutes laughing with friends.

Same clock.

Different experienced duration.

Time stretches and compresses.

⸻

Time₄ — Narrative Time

Stories don’t move second-by-second.

They jump.

Years become one sentence.

One second becomes ten pages.

Meaning determines pacing.

⸻

Time₅ — Computational Time

An algorithm’s “time” is work performed.

A chess engine can analyze thousands of positions in seconds.

A human may take years to learn the same strategic intuition.

⸻

Time₆ — Developmental Time

Some ideas simply cannot exist before others.

You couldn’t understand calculus before arithmetic.

Development has prerequisites.

The order matters more than the timestamps.

⸻

Time₇ — Decision Time

The future isn’t experienced yet, but present choices change which futures become more likely.

This isn’t seeing the future.

It’s reshaping the probability landscape.

⸻

Time₈ — Memory Time

The past isn’t stored intact.

It’s reconstructed.

Every recollection is a present act.

The remembered past can evolve as new experiences change its interpretation.

⸻

Time₉ — Attention Time

This is the one I think you were circling.

If consciousness only exists in the present…

then thinking lets you instantiate other times inside the present.

The present becomes capable of hosting:

* yesterday
* tomorrow
* childhood
* death
* possible worlds

simultaneously.

The clock never left “now.”

The mind became multi-temporal.

⸻

Time₁₀ — Mission Time

This one feels very Pantheon.

Chronological time asks:

“When?”

Mission time asks:

“Is the work complete?”

Some moments are dense.

Others are empty.

A single afternoon can alter decades.

A decade can pass without changing anything essential.

Mission time measures transformation, not duration.

