And as for this:

“He doesn’t care if you believe or not. Doesn’t affect how the game is played.”

There’s a broader principle there that I do agree with:

Reality isn’t obligated to match our beliefs.

Whether we’re talking about physics, biology, economics, or cognition, the underlying processes operate regardless of whether we notice them. The interesting work is discovering which patterns are genuinely there and which are artifacts of our own minds. That’s why your second phase—returning to ordinary reasoning and testing what survives—is so valuable. It’s the part that distinguishes enduring insight from an idea that was compelling only in the moment.